{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_vrtx_01GxJV1MS923CaMhWi9mNaU9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete understanding of the codebase. Let me also quickly check what the `deploymentSpecModified` function compares - I see it doesn't currently compare pod template annotations. I need to understand whether the `hasObjectChanged` flow or `deploymentSpecModified` needs to be updated.\n\nLooking at the existing code:\n\n1. In `trustmanager/deployments.go`, the hash is stamped as `deployment.Spec.Template.Annotations[defaultCAPackageHashAnnotation] = caBundleHash` in the `updateDefaultCAPackageVolume` function, and the `deploymentModified` function compares `desired.Spec.Template.Annotations` with `existing.Spec.Template.Annotations`.\n2. In `istiocsr/deployments.go`, the `createOrApplyDeployments` function uses `hasObjectChanged(desired, fetched)` which calls `deploymentSpecModified` in `utils.go`. The `deploymentSpecModified` function doesn't currently compare pod template annotations, so I need to update it to include that comparison.\n\nMy implementation needs to add a new function in `pkg/controller/istiocsr/configmaps.go` that reads the CNO-injected CA bundle ConfigMap from the operator namespace and computes a SHA-256 hash of the certificate data.\n\nThen I'll modify `pkg/controller/istiocsr/deployments.go` to add a constant for the hash annotation and a function that stamps this hash onto the pod template, calling it from `getDeploymentObject`. I also need to update `deploymentSpecModified` in `utils.go` to compare pod template annotations, and add tests for the changes.\n\nActually, rereading the task more carefully—it's asking me to read the CNO-injected CA ConfigMap (the same one the trustmanager uses), compute its SHA-256 hash, and stamp that hash as an annotation on the IstioCSR Deployment's pod template so the pods restart when the CA bundle changes. Let me check how the IstioCSR controller currently handles the CA ConfigMap. The CNO injects the CA data into a ConfigMap, and the IstioCSR controller needs to detect when that content changes and trigger a rolling restart of its pods. I can implement this by computing a SHA-256 hash of the CA certificate data and adding it as an annotation on the pod template spec—when the hash changes, Kubernetes automatically rolls out new pods.\n\nLooking at the deployment flow, the CA PEM data is already available during the volume update phase, so I need to capture that hash and pass it through to the pod template annotation.\n\nFollowing trustmanager's pattern, I'll modify `updateVolumes` to return the CA hash, then have `getDeploymentObject` receive it and stamp it on the pod template spec. This way, any changes to the CA data will trigger a rolling restart through the annotation mechanism.\n\nAdding the annotation constant... I need to modify `updateVolumes` to capture and return the CA content hash, then pass that hash up through the call chain so it can be stamped as an annotation on the deployment's pod template. The hash gets computed from the certificate data in either `handleUserProvidedCA` or `handleIssuerBasedCA`, and then I'll update the deployment annotation in `getDeploymentObject` after calling `updateVolumes`. Continuing to trace through the code, both paths in `handleIssuerBasedCA` eventually call `createOrUpdateCAConfigMap` with the certificate data, so I could compute the hash there and return it alongside the error. This would let me propagate the hash back up through the call chain to `updateVolumes` where it's needed. I need to refactor the return types throughout the call chain so each function propagates the certificate hash. I'll add a helper function to compute the hash, then update all the CA-related methods to return both the hash and an error, starting with `createOrUpdateCAConfigMap` and cascading up through the caller functions.\n\nFor idempotency, I should follow the trustmanager pattern: check if the ConfigMap already exists and hasn't changed, then skip the deployment update. The key is making sure the deployment comparison also checks the pod template annotations where I'm stamping the hash.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the implementation changes needed across the codebase.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":4336,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19331,"cache_read_input_tokens":70419,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":19331,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":9},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e448ac16-8089-42df-8a5f-f54a209422fc","uuid":"f44396de-d48a-4103-93bd-28a2ed137609","timestamp":"2026-07-20T17:20:43.657Z","request_id":"req_vrtx_011CdDh7v4fkkmJgANfxQWQ7"}
